Hey There!

  Saw some discussions about supporting iterables and I think your response there makes a lot of sense.  They are easy enough to coerce to standard arrays anyway.

  However, I can see the benefit in supporting, in some fashion, getting (and setting) of map values with the _.get and _.set  and friends. 

  Obviously we can only accept string keys when using the string-style paths, but could even support object and other keys if an array-style path is created instead.

  While maps don't have many of the issues that objects have, it can still be tremendously helpful when working with nested object values.  

```js
const obj = {
  map: new Map([['foo', 'bar'], ['baz', 'qux']]),
};

const foo = _.get(obj, 'map.foo')
_.set(obj, 'map.lux', 'dax')
// or
_.set(obj, [ 'map', { s: 'lux' } ], 'dax')
```

which could also go further 

```js
const obj = {
  map: new Map([['foo', 'bar'], ['baz', 'qux']]),
};

const foo = _.get(obj, 'map.foo')
_.set(obj, 'map.lux',{ val: 'dax' })

const luxVal = _.get(obj, 'map.foo.lux.val')
```

Similarly, it would make sense to handle sets as well for setting them similar to how an array is set/get.

